init_text: All of the "#1 Dad" mugs in the world change to show the actual ranking of Dads suddenly.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: After all, how did the surveyors possibly know who was the best at being a father?

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The letters were sent by a company called "Our Father, Inc."

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Their main product was a one-day seminar that would help you become the best possible father.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: They had a track record of getting parents' rankings way up.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The letter claimed that the course would teach you everything you needed to know about being a better father.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The letter came with a form to sign up for the course.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The response to this letter was enormous.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Buzzfeed had obtained a copy of the "Our Father, Inc." course.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It turns out that "Our Father, Inc." is also a company that makes coffee mugs.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And they make mugs that change depending on your ranking.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The company's website is now down.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And the coffee mugs that were being sold are available, marked down to under $10.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: But the idea of these magic mugs still lingers.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And so, if you Google "Our Father, Inc." you get this:
